      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the very comfortable end of your easy range — conversational pace, relaxed shoulders, easy breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Maintain steady easy effort throughout. You should be able to hold a full conversation. Focus on relaxed form and consistent cadence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually ease off to a comfortable walk-jog finish. Light stretching afterward, paying attention to your IT band.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of very easy running or brisk walking to get the legs moving.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"End with a gentle walk and 5–10 minutes of dynamic stretching. Give your IT band and hips some extra attention — leg swings and lateral hip stretches are a good call here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic day — the bread and butter of half-marathon training. Running at your Daniels-Gilbert easy pace (5:52–6:43/km) builds aerobic capacity, improves fat metabolism, and allows your musculoskeletal system to adapt without accumulating excessive stress. With your IT band history, keeping this genuinely easy is especially important early in the block. Resist the urge to push — the physiological benefit happens because of consistent easy running, not despite it.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":293,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10–15 minutes easy running to elevate heart rate gradually. Include 4–6 light strides of 20 seconds in the final 3 minutes to prime the legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":293,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First threshold rep at 4:53/km — comfortably hard, controlled breathing. You should be able to speak in short phrases but not full sentences.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery — keep moving, don't stop. Let your breathing settle before the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":293,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second threshold rep — same controlled effort. Focus on relaxed form at this pace, not grinding.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery again. Check in with your body — any tightness in the hip or lateral knee? Adjust if needed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":293,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third rep — finish strong but controlled. This is not a race effort; maintain the same pace you started with.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog back to complete the session. Gradual wind-down is important after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running with light strides at the end. Don't skip this — threshold work on cold legs is both less effective and higher risk.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10–15 minutes very easy jogging, then hip flexor and IT band stretches. Foam rolling the lateral quad is a smart choice given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running is the cornerstone of half-marathon fitness — it raises your lactate threshold, the physiological ceiling that determines your sustainable race pace. Using cruise intervals (3 × 8 min with 2 min jog recovery) rather than one continuous tempo run allows you to accumulate more quality time at threshold with better form. Your Daniels-Gilbert threshold pace is 4:53/km. The goal is controlled discomfort — not a red-line effort. This session builds the aerobic engine that will carry you through the back half of your race.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":46,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":403,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":403,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":46,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this at the slower end of your easy range (6:30–6:43/km). This run is about active recovery and adding aerobic volume without taxing your system. If the legs feel heavy from Wednesday, slow down further — there is no benefit in pushing here.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the first 5 minutes of the run itself acts as your warmup. Start very gently.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2–3 minutes at the finish. IT band stretch, hip flexor stretch, and calf stretch are all worthwhile.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sandwiched between your tempo day and your weekend quality work, this run serves a deliberate recovery purpose. Running at the lower end of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone promotes blood flow and clearance of metabolic byproducts without adding meaningful physiological load. Think of it as active recovery with mileage credit. Keeping this genuinely easy is one of the more important discipline habits in your training week.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":270,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy running. Include 4–6 × 20-second strides with full recovery in the final few minutes to prime your neuromuscular system for interval effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":270,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 × 3-minute intervals at 4:30/km (your Daniels-Gilbert interval pace). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — a 9/10 effort that you could sustain for another minute if you absolutely had to. Run with tall posture and relaxed arms.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"3 minutes easy jog between each interval. Recover fully enough to hit the next rep at the same pace — if you're still gasping at 3 minutes, take an extra 60 seconds.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 10–15 minute jog to bring heart rate down gradually. Don't stop immediately after the last interval.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 15-minute warmup with strides is non-negotiable for interval work. Your muscles and cardiovascular system need to be primed before hitting VO2max intensity.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging, then a thorough stretch. IT band, hip flexors, quads. Hydrate well — interval sessions are dehydrating.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the highest-intensity work in your plan and the most potent stimulus for improving maximal aerobic capacity. Running at 4:30/km (your Daniels-Gilbert interval pace) stresses your oxygen uptake system maximally, leading to cardiovascular and muscular adaptations that raise your ceiling for sustained fast running. For a 1:45 half-marathon goal, improving VO2max is essential — it creates headroom above your race pace. The 5 × 3-minute format is a proven entry point that delivers the stimulus without excessive fatigue. Keep the recovery jogs truly easy.\",\"perceived_effort\":9},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Sunday Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":103,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 8–10 minutes at the very easy end of your range. Ease into the run — long runs are not races.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":85,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy effort throughout at 5:52–6:43/km. Aim for even effort, not even pace — if you hit a hill, let your effort guide you rather than chasing the pace. This is an aerobic endurance run, not a progression run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes at a noticeably comfortable pace. Walk the last 2–3 minutes if you like.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start slow and let the first mile be your warmup. Hydrate before you head out and carry fluids if it's warm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes, then a thorough stretch session — hip flexors, IT band, glutes, calves. This is the most important cooldown of your week. Consider foam rolling the lateral quad after.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the single most important workout in half-marathon training. It builds your aerobic base, trains your body to use fat as fuel, strengthens connective tissue, and develops the mental resilience to run for extended periods. At 16 km this week (a modest step up from your recent 14 km), you're building toward the 18–20 km range that will give you genuine confidence for race day. The pace should feel easy enough that you finish feeling like you could have kept going — that is not weakness, that is correct execution. Your IT band responded well to treatment, but long runs are when that history matters most, so stay tuned in to how the lateral knee feels.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
